Since the product xy is a linear combination of elements of this form, it follows that R is a subring of \mathbb {L}.

More concretely, let S be a set of points on the plane. For any two distinct points P_{1},P_{2}\in  S with P_{1}\neq  P_{2}, we denote the set of points (i.e., the subset of S):
P_{1}P_{2}=\hbox {line passing through }P_{1}\hbox { and }P_{2}
C(P_{1},P_{2})=\hbox {circle centered at }P_{1}\hbox { and passing through }P_{2}.
From S we may construct a new point Q by:

Given points P_{1},P_{2},Q_{1},Q_{2}\in  S, marking Q\in  P_{1}P_{2}\cap  Q_{1}Q_{2};

Given points P_{1},P_{2},O,P\in  S, and marking Q\in  P_{1}P_{2}\cap  C(O,P);

Given points O,O',P,P'\in  S, and marking Q\in  C(O,P)\cap  C(O',P').

A point P is called Constructible from S if there exists a sequence of sets
S=S_{0}\subset  S_{1}\subset  S_{2}\subset …\subset  S_{n}
where each S_{i}=S_{i-1}\cup \{P_{i}\} for a point P_{i} directly constructible from S_{i-1}, and P=P_{n}.

